[Solution]
{"0": "To find the area of the quadrilateral \\(ABCD\\) with vertices \\(A(0,1)\\), \\(B(1,3)\\), \\(C(5,2)\\), and \\(D(4,0)\\), we can use the Shoelace Theorem. This theorem states that for a polygon with vertices \\((x_1, y_1), (x_2, y_2), \\ldots, (x_n, y_n)\\), the area \\(A\\) is given by:\n\\[ A = \\frac{1}{2} \\left| x_1y_2 + x_2y_3 + \\cdots + x_{n-1}y_n + x_ny_1 - (y_1x_2 + y_2x_3 + \\cdots + y_{n-1}x_n + y_nx_1) \\right| \\]", "1": "For our quadrilateral \\(ABCD\\), the vertices in order are \\(A(0,1)\\), \\(B(1,3)\\), \\(C(5,2)\\), and \\(D(4,0)\\). Plugging these into the Shoelace Theorem, we get:\n\\[ A = \\frac{1}{2} \\left| 0\\cdot3 + 1\\cdot2 + 5\\cdot0 + 4\\cdot1 - (1\\cdot1 + 3\\cdot5 + 2\\cdot4 + 0\\cdot0) \\right| \\]", "2": "Simplifying inside the absolute value:\n\\[ A = \\frac{1}{2} \\left| 0 + 2 + 0 + 4 - (1 + 15 + 8 + 0) \\right| \\]\n\\[ A = \\frac{1}{2} \\left| 6 - 24 \\right| \\]\n\\[ A = \\frac{1}{2} \\left| -18 \\right| \\]\n\\[ A = \\frac{1}{2} \\times 18 = 9 \\]", "3": "Therefore, the area of quadrilateral \\(ABCD\\) is \\(\\boxed{9}\\)."}

