[Question]
Expand and simplify completely: \begin{align*}
x\left(x(1+x)+2x\right)-3(x^2-x+2)
\end{align*}

[Solution]
{"0": "To expand and simplify the given expression, we'll follow the order of operations (PEMDAS): Given expression: \\begin{align*} x\\left(x(1+x)+2x\\right)-3(x^2-x+2) \\end{align*}", "1": "Step 1: Distribute x to the terms inside the first parenthesis. Inside the first parenthesis: $x(1+x)+2x$ Distributing x: \\begin{align*} x(1+x) &= x \\cdot 1 + x \\cdot x = x + x^2 \\\\ x(1+x)+2x &= x + x^2 + 2x \\end{align*} So, the expression becomes: \\begin{align*} x\\left(x + x^2 + 2x\\right)-3(x^2-x+2) \\end{align*}", "2": "Step 2: Distribute x to the terms inside the first parenthesis. Distributing x: \\begin{align*} x\\left(x + x^2 + 2x\\right) &= x \\cdot x + x \\cdot x^2 + x \\cdot 2x \\\\ &= x^2 + x^3 + 2x^2 \\end{align*} So, the expression becomes: \\begin{align*} x^2 + x^3 + 2x^2 -3(x^2-x+2) \\end{align*}", "3": "Step 3: Distribute -3 to the terms inside the second parenthesis. Distributing -3: \\begin{align*} -3(x^2-x+2) &= -3x^2 + 3x - 6 \\end{align*} So, the expression becomes: \\begin{align*} x^2 + x^3 + 2x^2 -3x^2 + 3x - 6 \\end{align*}", "4": "Step 4: Combine like terms. Combining like terms: \\begin{align*} x^2 + x^3 + 2x^2 -3x^2 + 3x - 6 &= x^3 + (x^2 - 3x^2 + 2x^2) + 3x - 6 \\\\ &= x^3 + (-3x^2 + 2x^2) + 3x - 6 \\\\ &= x^3 + (-x^2) + 3x - 6 \\\\ &= x^3 - x^2 + 3x - 6 \\end{align*}", "5": "Therefore, the simplified expression is: \\boxed{x^3 - x^2 + 3x - 6}"}

