[Question]
Given regular pentagon $ABCDE,$ a circle can be drawn that is tangent to $\overline{DC}$ at $D$ and to $\overline{AB}$ at $A.$ In degrees, what is the measure of minor arc $AD$? [asy]import olympiad; import geometry; size(100); defaultpen(linewidth(0.8));
pair[] pentagon = new pair[5];
pentagon[0] = dir(36);
pentagon.cyclic=true;
for(int i = 1; i < 6; ++i){

pentagon[i] = dir(72*i + 36);

draw(pentagon[i - 1]--pentagon[i]);
}
dot("$C$",pentagon[0],NE);
dot("$D$",pentagon[1],N);
dot("$E$",pentagon[2],W);
dot("$A$",pentagon[3],S);
dot("$B$",pentagon[4],SE);
line x = line(pentagon[1],pentagon[1] + dir(-108));
line x2 = line(origin,pentagon[2]);
pair ccenter = coordinates(intersectionpoint(x,x2));
draw(Circle(ccenter,arclength(ccenter--pentagon[1])));
[/asy]

[Solution]
{"0": "To determine the measure of the minor arc \\(AD\\) in the given circle that is tangent to \\(\\overline{DC}\\) at \\(D\\) and to \\(\\overline{AB}\\) at \\(A\\), we need to analyze the geometric properties of the regular pentagon and the circle. First, recall that a regular pentagon has five equal sides and five equal interior angles. The measure of each interior angle of a regular pentagon is given by: \\[ \\frac{(5-2) \\times 180^\\circ}{5} = \\frac{3 \\times 180^\\circ}{5} = 108^\\circ. \\] Thus, each interior angle of the pentagon \\(ABCDE\\) is \\(108^\\circ\\).", "1": "Since the circle is tangent to \\(\\overline{DC}\\) at \\(D\\) and to \\(\\overline{AB}\\) at \\(A\\), the radii of the circle drawn to the points of tangency \\(D\\) and \\(A\\) are perpendicular to the tangents at these points. Therefore, \\(\\angle ODC = 90^\\circ\\) and \\(\\angle OAB = 90^\\circ\\), where \\(O\\) is the center of the circle.", "2": "Next, consider the quadrilateral \\(ODAB\\). Since \\(\\angle ODC = 90^\\circ\\) and \\(\\angle OAB = 90^\\circ\\), the sum of the interior angles of quadrilateral \\(ODAB\\) is: \\[ \\angle ODC + \\angle OAB + \\angle DAB + \\angle DOA = 360^\\circ. \\] We know that \\(\\angle DAB = 108^\\circ\\) (since it is an interior angle of the pentagon). Substituting the known values, we get: \\[ 90^\\circ + 90^\\circ + 108^\\circ + \\angle DOA = 360^\\circ. \\]", "3": "Simplifying this equation, we find: \\[ 288^\\circ + \\angle DOA = 360^\\circ, \\] so \\[ \\angle DOA = 72^\\circ. \\]", "4": "The measure of the minor arc \\(AD\\) is equal to the measure of the central angle \\(\\angle DOA\\). Therefore, the measure of the minor arc \\(AD\\) is: \\[ \\boxed{72}. \\]"}

[Question]
How many rectangles are in the array below?

[asy]
for(int i = 0; i<3; ++i)
{

for(int j = 0; j<3; ++j)

{

draw((3i,j)--(3i+3,j)--(3i+3,j+1)--(3i,j+1)--(3i,j)--cycle,linewidth(2));

}
}
[/asy]

[Solution]
{"0": "To count the total number of rectangles in the given array, we can break down the task into smaller steps. First, consider the single squares. Each small square is considered as one rectangle. There are \\(3 \\times 3 = 9\\) single squares.", "1": "Second, consider rectangles composed of 2 squares. These can be either horizontally or vertically aligned.", "2": "Horizontally, you can pick any two out of three columns to form a rectangle. Since there are 3 choices for the first column and 2 choices for the second column (since it cannot be the same), this gives us \\(3 \\times 2 = 6\\) rectangles. However, each pair of columns can start from any row, so we multiply by 3 (the number of rows), giving \\(6 \\times 3 = 18\\) rectangles.", "3": "Vertically, similarly, you can pick any two out of three rows to form a rectangle. This also gives us \\(18\\) rectangles since the logic is symmetric.", "4": "Third, consider rectangles composed of 3 squares. These are larger rectangles that span across the entire grid. You can choose any two out of the three rows and any two out of the three columns to form such a rectangle. The number of ways to choose two rows out of three is \\(C(3,2) = 3\\), and similarly, the number of ways to choose two columns out of three is also \\(3\\). Therefore, the total number of rectangles composed of 3 squares is \\(3 \\times 3 = 9\\).", "5": "Finally, adding all these up:\n- Single squares: \\(9\\)\n- Rectangles composed of 2 squares: \\(18\\)\n- Rectangles composed of 3 squares: \\(9\\)", "6": "Total number of rectangles = \\(9 + 18 + 9 = 36\\).", "7": "Therefore, the total number of rectangles in the given array is **36**."}
